ie Lythcott-Haims\r\n2015","link_url":"https://www.amazon.com/How-Raise-Adult-Overparenting-Prepare/dp/1250093635/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*Bi Any Other Name - Bisexual People Speak Out*","blurb":"The \"B\" in the acronym LGBTQ (or LGBTQ+) stands for the bisexual* community; an often misrepresented and misunderstood group silenced by biphobia, bierasure and other fear based internalizations/projections within the LGBTQ community as well as outside of it. Large portions of the bisexual community are comprised of transgender people and people of color, and while the bisexual community is the single largest group within the LGBTQ community, it is one of the most at risk populations within it (according to a 2015 published study by BinetUSA, The Bisexual Organizing Project, and the Bisexual Resource Center in partnership with The Human Rights Campaign). Thanks to this groundbreaking book a generation of previously unseen bisexuals has been given a voice, and a new genre for books on bisexuality has been created. It was also named one of Lamda Book Report’s Top 100 Queer Books of the 20th Century. Education and knowledge is power. In the spirit of empowering ourselves, each other and our LGBTQ youth, I strongly encourage reading this book to understand the nuances and history of the bisexual community. \r\n\r\n*The term bisexual will be used as an inclusive term to mean romantic and/or sexual attraction to more than one gender, and includes pansexual, fluid, omnisexual and queer self-identifications.","note":"Edited by Loraine Hutchins and Lani Ka'ahumanu\r\nRiverdale Avenue Books, 2015","link_url":"https://www.amazon.com/Bi-Any-Other-Name-Bisexual/dp/1626011990/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"EX